<dl id="un6019ds"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un6" href="#un6019">UN6: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un6all.htm#un6019ds"> (NLI.4) 19(ds)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pupils dilate close eyes <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un6019ds"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/t/lext.htm#un6019ds">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/t/t86.htm#un6019ds">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/t/t86.htm#un6019ds">1986 (18.153)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/t/l22t.htm#un6019ds">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#un6019ds">MS TS-B</ms> </li><li>JJA 16:303 </li><li><a name="td4" href="../udra/u18da.htm#td4">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/t/td4.htm#un6019ds">Draft: 18.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Summarized in <cite>Archives d&apos;Anthropologie Criminelle</cite>, March, 1903, p. 188. The tendency to <mark>closure of the eyes</mark> noted by Roubaud, to avoid contact of the light, indicates <mark>dilatation of the pupils</mark>, for which we need not seek other explanation than the general tendency of all peripheral stimulation, according to Schiff&apos;s law, to produce such dilatation. <small> Havelock Ellis, <a name="HEPS" href="/udra/udex.htm#HEPS"><cite title="source">Studies in the Psychology of Sex</cite></a> (1906), vol. V, 152n</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
